               <desc type="building-data" xml:lang="en"> Eastward facing, north of the Lü (Dongbin) Temple-pavilion, connected to the Reading Terrace also located to its south. Constructed at the beginning of the Guangxu reign period (1875-1909) by the abbot monk Xutan 續曇 who raised the money to have it built. According to 晉祠志, the triple-terrace represents the emperor's three terraces: a spiritual terrace (靈臺), a seasonal terrace (時臺), and a park terrace for observing birds and beasts (囿臺). The 天文志 documents the three terraces as composing of six stars in charge of destiny, official rank (nobility), and salary/earning.
               </desc>
